{"title_page": "Ralph Hone", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n[[Major-General]] '''Sir Herbert Ralph Hone'''  {{Post-nominals|KCMG|KBE|MC}} (3 May 1896 \u2013 28 November 1992) was a [[British Army]] officer, barrister and colonial administrator.\n\n==Life up to World War II==\nRalph Hone was born in [[Hove]], Sussex, and was educated at [[Varndean College|Varndean Grammar School]], [[Brighton]]. Hone's mother died while he was in his teens; his father, \"a man of character\",<ref>Obituary in ''[[The Independent]]'' (4 December 1992)</ref> went on to become [[mayor]] of Brighton in 1937. His family, the [[Hone family|Hones]], were distant relations to [[Nathaniel Hone the Elder]] of the famous painting, writing, cricket and diplomatic dynasty the Hones. However, Ralph's upbringing was far removed from that of his forebears.\n\nIn April 1915 Hone passed the British civil service examination. He then joined the [[Inns of Court Regiment]] and was commissioned in July 1915 in the [[London Irish Rifles]].<ref>[http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/29242/pages/7342 ''London Gazette'' Issue 29242] published on the 27 July 1915. Page 22</ref> He was posted to the 1/18th battalion and was involved in the [[Battle of Loos]] in autumn 1915. Hone served in the [[Notre Dame de Lorette]] sector and then at [[Battle of Vimy Ridge|Vimy Ridge]]. During this time Hone was hospitalised with acute [[trench fever]] and [[impetigo]]. He was promoted to lieutenant on 14 April 1917,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=30097|supp=y|page=5217|date=25 May 1917}}</ref> and to acting captain on 14 January 1918.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=30799|supp=y|page=8420|date=16 July 1918}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March 1918 the Germans opened their [[Spring Offensive]] with 6000 guns. Hone's company halted the German's first infantry assault, capturing 25 German prisoners. Hone was awarded the [[Military Cross]] (MC) for his actions when the Germans attempted to [[enfilade]] the British lines, becoming severely wounded in the process.<ref>[http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/30901/supplements/10966 ''London Gazette'' Issue 30901] published on the 13 September 1918. Page 114/5</ref> He was repatriated to England, and by the end of the war had been promoted to a [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]]. The day after the [[Armistice with Germany|Armistice]] he married Elizabeth Matthews (b. 1894/5), with whom he later had two children, a son and daughter.\n\nIn 1920 Hone left the army and joined the colonial service in Uganda. He trained as a [[barrister]] and on his first long leave was [[call to the bar|called to the bar]] by the [[Middle Temple]] in 1924, during which time he aided in the prosecution of Patrick Mahon, the perpetrator of the [[Crumbles murders]]. The next year he was appointed [[Zanzibar]]'s registrar to the high court; followed by resident magistrate. His legal career continued with an appointment as crown counsel in [[Tanganyika Territory|Tanganyika]], followed by [[Attorney General of Gibraltar]] (1933\u201336). While he was in Gibraltar the [[Spanish Civil War]] broke out; domestic duties included acting as chairman of the Gibraltar government [[slum clearance]] commission. From Gibraltar he was posted to [[Uganda]] from 1937 to 1943, as [[Attorney General of Uganda]].\n\n==World War II==\nHone was made commandant of the Uganda Defence Force following the outbreak of the Second World War. In 1941 he was transferred to [[Middle East Command|General Headquarters Middle East]], first as legal advisor to advise on law in the conquered Italian territories and later as chief political officer. In March 1943 he was promoted to [[major-general]], \"to ease his command over the Brigadiers under him\";<ref>Obituary in ''[[The Independent]]'' (4 December 1992)</ref> he was also appointed [[CBE]]. This was followed by a period in the [[War Office]] in London, dealing with the war situation in [[Pacific War|South-East Asia]]. While working at [[South East Asia Command]] (SEAC) headquarters he got to know [[Louis Mountbatten]], later Earl Mountbatten of Burma. In August 1945 Hone was sent to [[British Malaya|Malaya]], to oversee the handover to civilian rule, and was present at the [[Surrender of Japan|Japanese surrender]] at [[Singapore]] on 12 September.\n\n==Post-war career==\nHone married again in 1945, and had a son by his second wife Sybil. Hone was awarded the [[KBE]] in 1946. He served as Secretary-General to the Governor-General of Malaya for two years from 1946, followed by Deputy Commissioner-General in south-east Asia from 1948 to 1949, and in 1949 he was appointed [[Governor of North Borneo|Governor]] and Commander-in-Chief of [[North Borneo]].<ref>Obituary in the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'' (7 December 1992)</ref> Hone was considered a great success as Governor of North Borneo, encouraging the country's recovery from the ravages of the Japanese occupation and expanding the colony's export trades. He was appointed {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|KCMG}} in 1951.\n\n==Final years of his career==\n[[File:NorthBorneoRailways-SteamLocomotive-SirRalphHone-02.jpg|thumb|\"Sir H. Ralph Hone\" displayed in the [[Sabah Museum]]]]\nHone was head of the legal division of the Commonwealth Relations Office from 1954 to 1961, when he retired from the civil service, and resumed practice at the bar. Given his background in diplomacy and overseas service, he also held many important advisory posts both at home and overseas: his final advisership was to the [[Bermuda]]n government from July to November 1966.\n\nHone was Vice President of the [[Royal Commonwealth Society]]. He was also an active [[freemason]], a member of the higher degree of freemasonry, the Ancient and Accepted (Scottish) Rite 33\u00ba.<ref>{{cite web\n  | title =A Wink, a Nod, or a Shake of the Hand\n  | publisher =Kate Sharpley Library, originally published in Anarchy magazine\n  | url =http://www.katesharpleylibrary.net/masons.htm\n  | accessdate =28 June 2007 }}</ref>\nHone was also Bailiff Grand Cross of the [[Venerable Order of St John]]. He died on 28 November 1992.\n\nAn archive of Hone's papers dating from 1937 to 1972 has been deposited at the [[Bodleian Library]] of Commonwealth and African Studies at [[Rhodes House]], part of the [[University of Oxford]]. The reference for the records is MSS Brit Emp s 407, MSS Ind Ocn s 271.<ref>{{cite web\n  | title =National Register of Archives: Hone, Sir Herbert Ralph Knight Major General Colonial Administrator\n  | publisher =The National Archives\n  | url =http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/nra/searches/pidocs.asp?P=P14358\n  | accessdate =28 June 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn addition, the papers of Louis Francis Albert Victor Nicholas George Mountbatten, 1st Earl Mountbatten of Burma held at [[Southampton University]] Library include correspondence with Hone relating to South East Asia Command 1944\u20131946. The reference for the records is MB1/C124.\n\nA steam engine was named in his honour, the [[Hunslet Engine Company|Hunslet]]-built 40604T \"Sir H. Ralph Hone\", which is now displayed in the [[Sabah Museum]], [[Kota Kinabalu]], [[Sabah]].<ref>{{cite web\n  | title =Sir H. Ralph Hone\n  | publisher =Narrow Gauge Heaven\n  | url =http://www.narrow-gauge.co.uk/gallery/show.php?cat_id=97&image_id=2773\n  | accessdate =25 June 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Publications by Sir Herbert Ralph Hone==\n*''Revised Edition of the Laws of Gibraltar in Force on 31 December 1935'' Gibraltar: Benedict R Miles for Gibraltar Garrison Library Committee, 1936\n*''The Statute Law of the Bahama Islands, 1799\u20131965 in Force on 1 April 1965'' Nassau: Government of the Colony of the Bahama Islands, 1965  \n*''The Subsidiary Legislation of the Bahama Islands, 1799\u20131965'' Nassau: Government of the Colony of the Bahama Islands, 1965\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Governor of North Borneo]] | before=[[Edward Francis Twining]] | after=Sir [[Roland Evelyn Turnbull]] | years=1950\u20131954 }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'' entry for Sir Herbert Ralph Hone by Philip Warner \n* Obituary in ''[[The Independent]]'' (4 December 1992) \n* Obituary in the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'' (7 December 1992) \n* Obituary in ''[[The Times]]'' (7 December 1992) \n* ''[[The Times]]'' (10 February 1993)\n* [http://janus.lib.cam.ac.uk/db/node.xsp?id=EAD%2FGBR%2F0115%2FY3021B Cambridge University Library: Royal Commonwealth Society Collections Sir Ralph Hone Collection: Saudi Arabia]\n* [http://www.kcl.ac.uk/lhcma/locreg/HONE.shtml Liddel Hart Centre for Military Archives entry for Sir Herbert Ralph Hone]\n*[http://www.britishmilitaryhistory.co.uk/documents.php?aid=117&nid=16&start=5 Major General Sir Herbert Ralph HONE] - Biographies at www.BritishMilitaryHistory.co.uk\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hone, Herbert Ralph}}\n[[Category:1896 births]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Hove]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:Governors of North Borneo]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Military Cross]]\n[[Category:Colonial Legal Service officers]]\n[[Category:Attorneys-General of Gibraltar]]\n[[Category:Attorneys General of the Uganda Protectorate]]\n[[Category:London Regiment officers]]\n[[Category:English barristers]]\n[[Category:English people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:British Army generals of World War II]]\n[[Category:British colonial army officers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n[[Major-General]] '''Sir Herbert Ralph Hone'''  {{Post-nominals|KCMG|KBE|MC}} (3 May 1896 \u2013 28 November 1992) was a [[British Army]] officer, barrister and colonial administrator.\n\n==Life up to World War II==\nRalph Hone was born in [[Hove]], Sussex, and was educated at [[Varndean College|Varndean Grammar School]], [[Brighton]]. Hone's mother died while he was in his teens; his father, \"a man of character\",<ref>Obituary in ''[[The Independent]]'' (4 December 1992)</ref> went on to become [[mayor]] of Brighton in 1937. His family, the [[Hone family|Hones]], were distant relations to [[Nathaniel Hone the Elder]] of the famous painting, writing, cricket and diplomatic dynasty the Hones. However, Ralph's upbringing was far removed from that of his forebears.\n\nIn April 1915 Hone passed the British civil service examination. He then joined the [[Inns of Court Regiment]] and was commissioned in July 1915 in the [[London Irish Rifles]].<ref>[http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/29242/pages/7342 ''London Gazette'' Issue 29242] published on the 27 July 1915. Page 22</ref> He was posted to the 1/18th battalion and was involved in the [[Battle of Loos]] in autumn 1915. Hone served in the [[Notre Dame de Lorette]] sector and then at [[Battle of Vimy Ridge|Vimy Ridge]]. During this time Hone was hospitalised with acute [[trench fever]] and [[impetigo]]. He was promoted to lieutenant on 14 April 1917,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=30097|supp=y|page=5217|date=25 May 1917}}</ref> and to acting captain on 14 January 1918.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=30799|supp=y|page=8420|date=16 July 1918}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March 1918 the Germans opened their [[Spring Offensive]] with 6000 guns. Hone's company halted the German's first infantry assault, capturing 25 German prisoners. Hone was awarded the [[Military Cross]] (MC) for his actions when the Germans attempted to [[enfilade]] the British lines, becoming severely wounded in the process.<ref>[http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/30901/supplements/10966 ''London Gazette'' Issue 30901] published on the 13 September 1918. Page 114/5</ref> He was repatriated to England, and by the end of the war had been promoted to a [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]]. The day after the [[Armistice with Germany|Armistice]] he married Elizabeth Matthews (b. 1894/5), with whom he later had two children, a son and daughter.\n\nIn 1920 Hone left the army and joined the colonial service in Uganda. He trained as a [[barrister]] and on his first long leave was [[call to the bar|called to the bar]] by the [[Middle Temple]] in 1924, during which time he aided in the prosecution of Patrick Mahon, the perpetrator of the [[Crumbles murders]]. The next year he was appointed [[Zanzibar]]'s registrar to the high court; followed by resident magistrate. His legal career continued with an appointment as crown counsel in [[Tanganyika Territory|Tanganyika]], followed by [[Attorney General of Gibraltar]] (1933\u201336). While he was in Gibraltar the [[Spanish Civil War]] broke out; domestic duties included acting as chairman of the Gibraltar government [[slum clearance]] commission. From Gibraltar he was posted to [[Uganda]] from 1937 to 1943, as [[Attorney General of Uganda]].\n\n==World War II==\nHone was made commandant of the Uganda Defence Force following the outbreak of the Second World War. In 1941 he was transferred to [[Middle East Command|General Headquarters Middle East]], first as legal advisor to advise on law in the conquered Italian territories and later as chief political officer. In March 1943 he was promoted to [[major-general]], \"to ease his command over the Brigadiers under him\";<ref>Obituary in ''[[The Independent]]'' (4 December 1992)</ref> he was also appointed [[CBE]]. This was followed by a period in the [[War Office]] in London, dealing with the war situation in [[Pacific War|South-East Asia]]. While working at [[South East Asia Command]] (SEAC) headquarters he got to know [[Louis Mountbatten]], later Earl Mountbatten of Burma. In August 1945 Hone was sent to [[British Malaya|Malaya]], to oversee the handover to civilian rule, and was present at the [[Surrender of Japan|Japanese surrender]] at [[Singapore]] on 12 September.\n\n==Post-war career==\nHone married again in 1945, and had a son by his second wife Sybil. Hone was awarded the [[KBE]] in 1946. He served as Secretary-General to the Governor-General of Malaya for two years from 1946, followed by Deputy Commissioner-General in south-east Asia from 1948 to 1949, and in 1949 he was appointed [[Governor of North Borneo|Governor]] and Commander-in-Chief of [[North Borneo]].<ref>Obituary in the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'' (7 December 1992)</ref> Hone was considered a great success as Governor of North Borneo, encouraging the country's recovery from the ravages of the Japanese occupation and expanding the colony's export trades. He was appointed {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|KCMG}} in 1951.\n\n==Final years of his career==\n[[File:NorthBorneoRailways-SteamLocomotive-SirRalphHone-02.jpg|thumb|\"Sir H. Ralph Hone\" displayed in the [[Sabah Museum]]]]\nHone was head of the legal division of the Commonwealth Relations Office from 1954 to 1961, when he retired from the civil service, and resumed practice at the bar. Given his background in diplomacy and overseas service, he also held many important advisory posts both at home and overseas: his final advisorship was to the [[Bermuda]]n government from July to November 1966.\n\nHone was Vice President of the [[Royal Commonwealth Society]]. He was also an active [[freemason]], a member of the higher degree of freemasonry, the Ancient and Accepted (Scottish) Rite 33\u00ba.<ref>{{cite web\n  | title =A Wink, a Nod, or a Shake of the Hand\n  | publisher =Kate Sharpley Library, originally published in Anarchy magazine\n  | url =http://www.katesharpleylibrary.net/masons.htm\n  | accessdate =28 June 2007 }}</ref>\nHone was also Bailiff Grand Cross of the [[Venerable Order of St John]]. He died on 28 November 1992.\n\nAn archive of Hone's papers dating from 1937 to 1972 has been deposited at the [[Bodleian Library]] of Commonwealth and African Studies at [[Rhodes House]], part of the [[University of Oxford]]. The reference for the records is MSS Brit Emp s 407, MSS Ind Ocn s 271.<ref>{{cite web\n  | title =National Register of Archives: Hone, Sir Herbert Ralph Knight Major General Colonial Administrator\n  | publisher =The National Archives\n  | url =http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/nra/searches/pidocs.asp?P=P14358\n  | accessdate =28 June 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn addition, the papers of Louis Francis Albert Victor Nicholas George Mountbatten, 1st Earl Mountbatten of Burma held at [[Southampton University]] Library include correspondence with Hone relating to South East Asia Command 1944\u20131946. The reference for the records is MB1/C124.\n\nA steam engine was named in his honour, the [[Hunslet Engine Company|Hunslet]]-built 40604T \"Sir H. Ralph Hone\", which is now displayed in the [[Sabah Museum]], [[Kota Kinabalu]], [[Sabah]].<ref>{{cite web\n  | title =Sir H. Ralph Hone\n  | publisher =Narrow Gauge Heaven\n  | url =http://www.narrow-gauge.co.uk/gallery/show.php?cat_id=97&image_id=2773\n  | accessdate =25 June 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Publications by Sir Herbert Ralph Hone==\n*''Revised Edition of the Laws of Gibraltar in Force on 31 December 1935'' Gibraltar: Benedict R Miles for Gibraltar Garrison Library Committee, 1936\n*''The Statute Law of the Bahama Islands, 1799\u20131965 in Force on 1 April 1965'' Nassau: Government of the Colony of the Bahama Islands, 1965  \n*''The Subsidiary Legislation of the Bahama Islands, 1799\u20131965'' Nassau: Government of the Colony of the Bahama Islands, 1965\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Governor of North Borneo]] | before=[[Edward Francis Twining]] | after=Sir [[Roland Evelyn Turnbull]] | years=1950\u20131954 }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'' entry for Sir Herbert Ralph Hone by Philip Warner \n* Obituary in ''[[The Independent]]'' (4 December 1992) \n* Obituary in the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'' (7 December 1992) \n* Obituary in ''[[The Times]]'' (7 December 1992) \n* ''[[The Times]]''